Part I
The body must be prepared with the utmost reverence. Wash it thoroughly with cold water and herbs to cleanse the spirit. The hair should be shorn close to the scalp, as it is a vessel for earthly concerns. The nails must be trimmed, as they are extensions of the mortal coil.

Part II
With solemn care, the internal organs must be removed. The heart, as the seat of the soul, should be preserved in a jar of brine. The other organs may be returned to the body or interred separately. To prevent decay, the body cavity must be filled with a mixture of salt, herbs, and myrrh. The eyes should be carefully removed and replaced with glass or gemstones to ward off evil spirits.

Part III
The body must be wrapped tightly in linen bandages to protect it from the elements. Each layer should be imbued with prayers and blessings. Aromatic resins, such as frankincense and myrrh, can be added to the bandages to mask the scent of decay and honor the departed. The head should be wrapped separately and adorned with a funerary mask.

Part IV
The coffin should be constructed of sturdy wood, preferably oak or cedar. It must be airtight to protect the body from desecration. The interior should be lined with soft fabrics and filled with aromatic herbs. The deceased should be placed in the coffin in a fetal position, symbolizing their return to the womb of the earth.

Each being has an eternal resting place that is chosen for him or her at the moment of creation. Life is a process of seeking that place and eternal rest. Existence is but a brief aberration in an eternity of death. Power, success, and joy are as transitory as weakness, failure, and misery. Only death is absolute, and then only at its appointed hour. Seek to bring order to the chaos of life, for in death there is finality and a fixedness of state. Be ready for death for it is at hand and uncompromising. Life should be prolonged only when it serves the greater cause of the death of the world.
